    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.6.8" />
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">McCLURES MAGAZINE
                        <lb/>
                    THE McCLURE PUBLICATIONS</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    25 West Forty-fourth St., New York
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">EDITORIAL DEPARTMENT</hi>
                </fw>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>June 12, 1919.</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you for your good letter, but it is I who should thank you. Your book really sticks in my memory and it stood out so tremendously among the mass of poetry on my desk that I could not help writing of it as I did. Immediately after I read it I asked Mr. Marsh to send me a copy of "The Song of Hugh Glass" and it has just come. I want to read that and I shall look forward to your third volume with greatest interest, I assure you.</p>
                
                <p>How good it is to think of a man living up to his ideals as you are doing! But that shows in your work, and that is the reason I could picture your life on the prairies as I did.</p>
                
                <p>Do write me again sometime. I should love to hear from you whenever you have the opportunity.</p>
                <closer>                
                    <salute>Faithfully yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Charlie Hamon Torrence</signed>
            
                    To:
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John G. Neihardt, Esq.,</addrLine>
                            <addrLine>Bancroft,</addrLine>
                                <addrLine>Nebraska.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
